http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/rss/-/1/hi/entertainment/6711947.stm sale for Mexican film star in the news Friday, 1 June 2007, 12:14 GMT 13:14 UK sale for Mexican film star Felix was Mexico's answer to Marilyn Monroe The estate of Mexican screen legend Maria Felix is to go up for auction next month. The Christie's sale in New York on 17 and 18 July includes clothing, film memorabilia and a portrait of her that has never been publicly exhibited. She was renowned as a femme fatale throughout Latin America and was the one-time lover of painter Diego Rivera. A portrait of her by Rivera is expected to fetch up to $200,000 (£100,000). Felix died at the age of 88 in 2002. But a 1965 surrealist portrait by Leonora Carrington, which has never been seen by the public, is estimated to sell for between $500,000 (£253,000) and $700,000 (£354,000). Over 600 lots are on offer, including pieces of antique furniture and jewellery. Some of the proceeds will go towards the Mexican Red Cross, Christie's said. Felix was nicknamed La Dona - which loosely translates as the Grand Dame - after the character from her breakthrough film Dona Barbara in 1943. She made 47 films in her career, though few of them were shown widely outside Spanish-speaking nations. Thousands of mourners turned out to pay their respects to Felix at her funeral in Mexico City. star 'died of natural causes' 01 Sep 02 | Film Mystery over Mexican 'Marilyn' death 01 Jun 07 | Film Mexico mourns its 'Marilyn' 09 Apr 02 | Showbiz Maria Felix official website The to become X Factor judge family barred from toilet Cannabis 'disrupts brain centre' Launch date for iPhone revealed New era of discord for Russia and West alternative Olympic logos Blair at centre of art show China's climate change stance a new challenge to UK policy? What do you think of the new logo for the London Olympics? What makes ordinary folk plunge into debt chasing celeb dream?
