http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/6716621.stm | Polish subtitles on Welsh TV show News in video and audio in the news Sunday, 3 June 2007, 13:10 GMT 14:10 UK subtitles on Welsh TV show Pc Keith Sinclair, from Wrexham, will feature in the programme Welsh language channel S4C is to broadcast a current affairs programme with Polish subtitles. O Flaen Dy Lygaid (Before Your Eyes), which is produced by the BBC, is thought to be the first TV show in the UK to use subtitles in Polish. The documentary will focus on Poles who moved to Wales decades before thousands settled after their nation joined the European Union in 2004. S4C said the subtitles were a one-off and it had no plans to do it regularly. The arrival of so many Poles in the UK has led to other initiatives such as Wales' first Polish support centre, which opened in Llanelli last year. In north Wales, an estimated 10,000 Poles live in Wrexham alone, which has prompted the region's police force to recruit Polish-speaking officers. O Flaen Dy Lygaid producer Marc Edwards said: "Polish people in Wales helped us enormously in making the documentary and were thrilled we were taking an interest in their community," he said. "The idea for subtitles in Polish really came from them. They wanted the programme to be available to Polish expats all over the UK and we were very happy to help make that happen." Emlyn Penny Jones, S4C's head of content services added that the channel was "delighted" to be making "broadcasting history". The programme will be presented by Barbara Owsianka who lives near Bangor in north Wales. Mrs Owsianka was born and raised in London after her parents fled Poland after World War II. She married a Welshman and they now raise their two children in three languages - Polish, Welsh and English. Wrexham policeman, Keith Sinclair, who learned Polish to work with the growing immigrant community, will also feature in the programme. O Flaen Dy Lygaid is on S4C on Tuesday, 5 June at 2100 BST information from across the region Get all the latest from around the region Polish minister could boost flock 29 Mar 07 | Mid Wales Migrant worker numbers 'unknown' 06 Mar 07 | Wales Honour for Pc who learned Polish 24 Nov 06 | North East Wales O Flaen Dy Lygaid The deaths road 'not gritted' Death crash driver 'fell asleep' Water tank crashes onto baby pen family barred from toilet Cannabis 'disrupts brain centre' Launch date for iPhone revealed New era of discord for Russia and West alternative Olympic logos Blair at centre of art show China's climate change stance a new challenge to UK policy? What do you think of the new logo for the London Olympics? What makes ordinary folk plunge into debt chasing celeb dream?
